{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}
The '''Clowns Gallery-Museum''' is a museum of [[clowning]] situated at venues in [[Holy Trinity Church, Dalston]] and [[Wookey Hole]], Somerset. Established in 1959, the collection contains costumes and props from famous clowns, as well as a reference library,<ref name="clowns">{{cite web | url=http://www.clowns-international.com/museum.html | title=The Clowns Gallery-Museum's History | publisher=Clowns International | accessdate=3 October 2015 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004154353/http://www.clowns-international.com/museum.html | archivedate=4 October 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and is home to the Clown Egg Register, an archive of painted ceramic and hen's eggs which serve as a record of individual clowns' personal make-up designs. The egg gallery was created because according to an unofficial rule, no two clowns are allowed to have the same make-up. In order to ensure that clowns weren’t copying each other’s makeup style, the practice of painting each unique design onto an egg began. Real eggs were originally used, but were later replaced with ceramic eggs. The gallery opens on the first Friday of each month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/attractions/clowns-gallery-museum-london|title=Clowns Gallery-Museum London|work=Time Out London|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref> The collection is split between the museum's two sites.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/56cac980-e8f9-11e2-aead-00144feabdc0.html | title=First Person: Matthew Faint – ‘I run the clown egg register’ | work=Financial Times | date=12 July 2013 | accessdate=3 October 2015 | author=Taylor, Jeremy}}</ref>

The museum was established in 1959 in Dalston and the collection was split to a venue in Wookey Hole in 2007. The Dalston museum is situated in what was the vestry of the Holy Trinity Church.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/jun/07/why-clowns-are-dying-out | title=Send out the clowns: why are they losing popularity? | publisher=The Guardian | date=7 June 2015 | accessdate=3 October 2015 | author=Adams, Tim}}</ref> It was threatened with closure in 2014, but remained in place.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://now-here-this.timeout.com/2015/01/30/a-matter-of-laugh-and-death-what-to-expect-at-the-joseph-grimaldi-service/ | title=A matter of laugh and death: what to expect at the Joseph Grimaldi service | publisher=Time Out | date=30 January 2015 | accessdate=3 October 2015 | author=Polyviou, Natasha}}</ref> The Wookey Hole museum is run by [[Gerry Cottle]], Vice President of [[Clowns International]].<ref name="clowns"/>

