==Review== In his ''New York Times'' review, Richard Eder writes the show is designed to be a musical show — there is no story line. He states that Ann Reinking is clearly the star and she is at her best in the high point of the evening, "Benny's Number", which recreates [[Benny Goodman]] and his band using "Sing, Sing, Sing". He also mentions several other dances, such as "Dancin' Man", with the entire cast dressed in "ice-cream" suits and lavender shirts; and "Fourteen Feet", where the shoes are nailed to the floor, and the dancers proceed to move within those confines. He sums up by writing "precision and style mark the evening at its best", but they serve very little.<ref>Eder, Richard. Review, ''The New York Times'', March 28, 1978, p. 48</ref>
Clive Barnes, newly moved to the ''New York Post'', told Fosse that he thought the show was "tremendous" and "fantastic".<ref name=Gottfried366 />
