{{BLP sources|date=December 2011}} {{Infobox officeholder | honorific_prefix = | name = Prof. Wanjiku Mukabi Kabira |honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Prof. Wanjiku Mukabi Kabira.jpg |office1 = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = |nickname = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1948|11|15|df=y}} | baptism_date = | birth_place = [[Kiambu]], Kenya | disappeared_date = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) --> | disappeared_place = | disappeared_status = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = | nationality = Kenyan | other_names = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Lecturer, Author, Director AWSC (University Of Nairobi) | employer = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | home_town = | television = | title = | term start = | term end = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | religion = | denomination = | criminal_charge = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources --> | criminal_penalty = | criminal_status = | spouse = {{marriage|Jackson Ntongai Kabira|1981}} | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Wanjiku Kabira''' is an associate professor of literature at the [[University of Nairobi]], [[Kenya]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/politics/-/1064/813888/-/wu9gi2z/-/index.html|title=Women praise proposed law’s provisions on gender equality|last=Okello|first=Rosemary|date=December 30, 2011|publisher=Daily Nation|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> She has specialized in the fields of [[Oral literature]], [[African-American literature]] and [[Caribbean literature]]. She has been actively involved in women affairs and in gender issues. Wanjiku has served as in various capacities notably as a. Vice-Chair in the Kenya Constitutional Review Process (2000-2005) b. Chair Person Women Political Alliance<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090715015733/http://www.ipsnews.net/africa/nota.asp?idnews=47632] </ref> (2002-2011) c. Director Collaborative Center for Gender and Development (1995-2009)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091127160556/http://www.ccentregd.org:80/downloads/Gender_lens.pdf] </ref> d. Chair, Department of Literature, University of Nairobi
==Work== Wanjiku Mukabi Kabira is a published author of young adult books. She has published widely on literature, women and on gender issues. One of her most notable books is ''A Letter to Mariama Ba'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110222233507/http://www.uonbi.ac.ke:80/press/catalogue/index.php?c=15&p=29] </ref> which was a response to ''[[So Long a Letter]]'', a book written by [[Mariama Bâ]]. Her work with women saw the founding of the African Women Studies Centre at the University of Nairobi in June, 2011, and in her tireless work with the Constitution of Kenya Review Commission. Her book, A Time for Harvest, traces the women’s journey in the struggle for a new constitution in the past 20 years, beginning from 1992 to 2012. She reminds the 16 women MPs of 290 that their mere presence in Parliament will be fruitless if it is not properly utilised.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/lifestyle/article/2000122190/scholar-who-walked-out-of-a-convent-to-study-in-the-us?pageNo=1 |title=Kenya : Scholar who walked out of a convent to study in the US - The Standard |website=Standardmedia.co.ke |date=2014-05-24 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>
Other published credits of Wanjiku Mukabi Kabira include ''[[Agikuyu]]'' (Heritage Library of African Peoples East Africa). Professor Wanjiku Kabira also has written many books about women and gender issues some of which include: ''Our Secret Lives''; ''They Have Destroyed the Temple''; ''Celebrating Women's Resistance''; ''The Oral Artist''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.ke/books/about/The_oral_artist.html?id=DMOQJAYUBEYC&redir_esc=y |title=The oral artist |website=Books.google.co.ke |date= |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>
==Early life== Prof. Wanjiku was born in 1948 in the present [[Lari Constituency]]. She went to school at Githirioni Primary School and later at [[Loreto High School, Limuru]] and Loreto Convent Msongari for her advanced certificate ('A' levels). She studied Literature, History and Scripture and received the 'Best Performing Student' prize in Literature.
